Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
addHaloToBlock(25.10)                                    addHaloToBlock(25.10)

Name
       addHaloToBlock - Adds a halo to a block

Syntax
       addHaloToBlock

       [-help]

       <left bottom right top>

       [-fromInstBox]

       [-snapToSite]

       [-ori <orientation>]

       [<inst_name>  |-allMacro  |  -allBlackBox | -allCommitPtn | -allBlock |
       -allIOPad | -cell <name>]

       Adds a halo to a block. A halo is an area that prevents  the  placement
       of  blocks  and  standard cells within the specified halo distance from
       the edges of a hard macro, black box, or committed partition  in  order
       to reduce congestion. A block halo value is specified based on the cur-
       rent block orientation. Use this command during or after floorplanning.
       You can use the deleteHaloFromBlock command to delete halos.

Parameters
       -allBlackBox
              Specifies halo values for all black boxes.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -allBlock
              Specifies halo values for all hard macros, black boxes, and com-
              mitted partitions.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -allCommitPtn
              Specifies halo values for all committed partitions.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -allIOPad
              Specifies halo values for all IO pads.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -allMacro
              Specifies halo values for all hard macros.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -cell <name>
              Specifies halo values for all instances of a cell.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -fromInstBox
              Creates  a block halo, based on the instance boundary, even when
              there is an overlap layer defined in the block cell or macro de-
              finition.

              Note: This parameter is for backward compatibility only. Cadence
              does not recommend the use of this parameter because  there  can
              be  problems  with the defin flow if this parameter is specified
              and if the block cell or the macro has overlap layers.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information  for  each  addHaloToBlock parameter. For a detailed
              description of the command and all of its  parameters,  use  the
              man command:

              man addHaloToBlock

       <inst_name>
              Specifies  the  block where the halo is to be added. You can use
              wildcards (* or ?) for specifying instance names.

              Data_type: string, optional

       <left bottom right top>
              Specifies the halo width on 4 sides. These  values  are  floats,
              units  are  microns.  Halo deltas are specified in relation to a
              block in R0 orientation (left is applied to  the  left  edge  of
              block  oriented  R0).  For  non-R0,  the  halo  deltas  are  ro-
              tated/flipped according to the blocks's orientation  (for  block
              oriented MY, the left halo delta specifies the width of the halo
              along the right side of the inst in the floorplan).

              * left:  the width of the halo along the left edge of insts hav-
                ing halos added.

              * bottom: the width of the halo along the bottom edge of objects
                having halos added.

              * right: the width of the halo along the right edge  of  objects
                having halos added.

              * top:  the width of the halo along the top edge of objects hav-
                ing halos added.

              Data_type: box, required

       -ori <orientation>
              Specifies the orientation value of the instances  to  which  the
              block  halo values are applied. The orientation value can be R0,
              R90, R180, R270, MX, MX90, MY, or MY90.

              Note: If the orientation is not set, the halo will be added with
              the current orientation of the macro.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -snapToSite
              Snaps the halo box to a site.

              Data_type: bool, optional

Example
       The following command adds a halo around block xy_inst:

       addHaloToBlock 10 20 30 40 xy_inst

       If xy_inst is R0, the halo width is 10 along the left edge and 30 along
       the right edge. If the block is MY, the halo width is 30 along the left
       edge in the floorplan, and 10 along the right edge in the floorplan.

       The following command adds a halo around all insts with cells  of  type
       myDRAMCell:

       addHaloToBlock 10 20 30 40 -cell myDRAMCell -ori MY

       If  the inst is oriented R0, then the left edge width of the halo is 30
       in the floorplan, and the right edge width of the halo is 10.

